  "text": "NEWS AND VIEWS 30 May 2025 In warming coastal seas, a crucial ecosystem is being replaced by ‘turfs’ of red algae, which release chemicals that suppress kelp survival. Credit: Alex Mustard/Nature Picture Library Great swathes of kelp provide shelter and food for marine life in reefs along many of the world’s coastlines. But these kelp forests (pictured) are under threat, partly because of rising ocean temperatures induced by climate change. When kelp forests collapse, carpets of red algae — known as turf algae — can take over the reef. Writing in Science, Farrell et al. explore the feedback loop that keeps turf algae on top ( S. P. Farrell et al . Science 388 , 876–880; 2025 ). Access options Access Nature and 54 other Nature Portfolio journals Get Nature+, our best-value online-access subscription $29.99 / 30 days cancel any time Subscribe to this journal Receive 51 print issues and online access $199.00 per year only $3.90 per issue Rent or buy this article Prices vary by article type from$1.95 to$39.95 Prices may be subject to local taxes which are calculated during checkout Additional access options: Log in Learn about institutional subscriptions Read our FAQs Contact customer support Nature 642, 40 (2025) doi: https://doi.org/10.1038/d41586-025-01692-x Competing Interests The author declares no competing interests. Related Articles Read the paper: Turf algae redefine the chemical landscape of temperate reefs, limiting kelp forest recovery Rethinking the effect of marine heatwaves on fish Metric for marine heatwaves suggests how these events displace ocean life See all News \u0026 Views Subjects Latest on:",
