  "html": "\u003cdiv id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"\u003e\u003cdiv data-container-type=\"article\" data-component=\"article-container\" id=\"content\" role=\"main\" aria-label=\"main page content\"\u003e\n        \n\n        \n            \n        \n        \n            \n                \u003carticle data-track-component=\"news\" lang=\"en\"\u003e\n                    \n\u003cdiv\u003e\n    \u003cheader\u003e\n        \u003cdiv\u003e\n            \u003cul data-test=\"article-identifier\"\u003e\n                \u003cli data-test=\"article-category\"\u003e\u003cspan\u003eNEWS AND VIEWS\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n                \u003cli\u003e\u003ctime datetime=\"2025-05-30\"\u003e30 May 2025\u003c/time\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n                \n            \u003c/ul\u003e\n\n            \n\n            \u003cdiv\u003e\n                \n                \u003cp\u003e\n                    In warming coastal seas, a crucial ecosystem is being replaced by ‘turfs’ of red algae, which release chemicals that suppress kelp survival.\n                \u003c/p\u003e\n            \u003c/div\u003e\n        \u003c/div\u003e\n        \n            \n        \n    \u003c/header\u003e\n    \n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n                    \u003cdiv\u003e\n                        \u003cfigure\u003e\n    \u003cpicture\u003e\n            \u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"\n                https://media.nature.com/w1248/magazine-assets/d41586-025-01692-x/d41586-025-01692-x_51028492.jpg?as=webp 1248w,\n                https://media.nature.com/w767/magazine-assets/d41586-025-01692-x/d41586-025-01692-x_51028492.jpg?as=webp 767w,\n                https://media.nature.com/w319/magazine-assets/d41586-025-01692-x/d41586-025-01692-x_51028492.jpg?as=webp 319w\" sizes=\"100vw, 767px\"/\u003e\n            \u003cimg aria-describedby=\"Fig2\" src=\"https://media.nature.com/w767/magazine-assets/d41586-025-01692-x/d41586-025-01692-x_51028492.jpg\" alt=\"Underwater scene of many branches of yellow-green giant kelp wafting in blue waters with a sea lion peeking out from behind a branch\"/\u003e\n    \u003c/picture\u003e\n    \u003cdiv\u003e\n        \u003cfigcaption\u003e\n            \u003cp id=\"Fig2\"\u003e Credit: Alex Mustard/Nature Picture Library\u003c/p\u003e\n        \u003c/figcaption\u003e\n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\u003c/figure\u003e\n                    \u003c/div\u003e\n                    \u003cdiv\u003e\n            \n            \n\n\n        \n            \n                \n                    \n                \n            \n\n            \n                \n\n                \n\n                \n                    \u003cp\u003eGreat swathes of kelp provide shelter and food for marine life in reefs along many of the world’s coastlines. But these kelp forests (pictured) are under threat, partly because of rising ocean temperatures induced by climate change. When kelp forests collapse, carpets of red algae — known as turf algae — can take over the reef. Writing in \u003ci\u003eScience\u003c/i\u003e, Farrell \u003ci\u003eet\u003c/i\u003e \u003ci\u003eal\u003c/i\u003e. explore the feedback loop that keeps turf algae on top (\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.1126/science.adt6788\" data-track=\"click\" data-label=\"https://doi.org/10.1126/science.adt6788\" data-track-category=\"body text link\"\u003e\nS. P. Farrell\n\u003ci\u003eet al\u003c/i\u003e\n.\n\u003ci\u003eScience\u003c/i\u003e\n\u003cb\u003e388\u003c/b\u003e\n, 876–880; 2025\n\u003c/a\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\n                    \u003cdiv\u003e\n                        \u003ch2 id=\"access-options\"\u003eAccess options\u003c/h2\u003e\n                        \n\n                        \n                            \n                                        \n        \n    \n\n                                \n    \n    \u003csection\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\n      \u003cp\u003e\n        Access Nature and 54 other Nature Portfolio journals\n      \u003c/p\u003e\n      \u003cp\u003e